title: For Sale:  One-of-a-kind folding AK stock
postcontent:
I have to sell this stock because it makes my weapon illegal in my home state of Michigan. 

This stock was originally a Russian triangle folding stock that had to be riveted into the receiver, which also had to be modified with a latch to hold the stock closed. Many of these were bought by the state arsenal in Bulgaria and fitted into a receiver block so they can be a drop in replacement for standard AKM stamped receiver stocks. Naturally this stock has a longer length of pull than the ones that just rivet in, which is a plus for most people of larger stature. This stock is very solid. There is NO slop at all when it is locked in the open position. There is a latch on the side of the receiver block that holds it in the closed position. The fit and finish of the stock is typical of any product from the state arsenal in Bulgaria and especially typical of an ARSENAL USA import. These people make the best AK rifles money can buy and they make the best parts. I personally bought mine from K-VAR, ARSENAL USA's distributor. MIDWAY USA still has the last of these stocks and they sell for $160.00 before tax and shipping. Mine is only very slightly used and doesn't have any finish wear so I think I have a very fair price on it. There is no tax, shipping charges, wait time, or shipping hassle for this product, so taking $50 off is a fair price. After all it is almost new. 

 Price is non negotiable. It deeply saddens me to have to get rid of this great part. I will be adding a picture of it on my rifle soon and I'll try to get a close up. I can be reached at REDACTED
-Anthony



 If you cannot view the image, please by all means text me for pictures of this wonderful stock.

postcontent:
I have a DPMS Panther Recon .223/5.56 rifle for sale. 

These are the specs from the manufacturer:

AAC Blackout Flash Hider, 416 Stainless steel button rifled heavy barrel with six grooves and right-hand 1x9 twist. Magpul BUIS Set Front and Rear sights. Upper Receiver: A3 Mil Spec Flat top, 7075-T6 aircraft aluminum alloy, hard coat anodized per Mil Spec and Teflon coated black, dust cover, shell deflector, round forward assist and right hand ejection. Lower Receiver: Forged 7075-T6 aircraft aluminum alloy, hard coat anodized per Mil Spec and Teflon coated black, semi-auto trigger group, Magpul MOE Trigger Guard, stock and pistol grip. Four rail DPMS Free Float mid length tube handguard. Weight: 7.7 pounds. Length: Extended: 35 1/2 inches, collapsed: 31 3/4 inches. Comes with 2- 30 round magazines, 1- nylon web sling and owners manual.

The rifle also comes with the Burris AR-332 fixed 3 power optic.  The optic reticle can be illuminated in either red or green, if not illuminated the reticle is black and always visible.  The optic also has a two inch sun shade that is removable and has flip up lense covers to protect the optic from dust and debris.  The Burris AR-332 is a quality budget optic, I zeroed it the day I got it and picked off targets easily at 300 yards from a prone position.  The reticle has 6 dots in 100 yard increments, so if you have in a gun vise and table you can really reach out and touch something.  I have had no issues what so ever with it and I'm very pleased with its performance. 

The package includes many extras.  The extras include: 6 Magpul 30 round Pmags (Used during the partial break in), around 20 +/- standard 30 round mags, three different Surefire Tactical flash lights that can be mounted on the rail, a GPS (grip pod system) that has built in bi-pod, and a box of federal ammunition that has over 700 rounds left (had 1000 when I bought it, so rifle has about 300 rounds shot through it).  I'm sure I'm forgetting some things but you get the picture.  This package has it all and if you were to go and buy it all brand new, you would spend well over $3000.  

I bought the rifle less than three weeks ago and have only shot it twice (about 300 rounds worth) so it's not even completely broke in.  I broke it in properly and used the Magpul Pmags.  I didn't even have a single issue with it.  I ran it very wet and didn't even have one failure to feed or failure to eject.  I've only shot 55 grain 5.56 through it.  From what I've heard the 1 in 9 twist barrel will have no problem shooting the 62 or 68 grain bullets as far as accuracy is concerned.  Not all extras are shown in pictures.  It's an awesome rifle and extremely fun to shoot.  Once you hold it in your hands you won't want to put it down.  Contact Brian with more questions/more pictures at REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  Pristine Russian M44 Mosin-Nagant Carbine w/Folding Bayonet
postcontent:
This Russian Mosin-Nagant M44 carbine was made in the Izhevsk arsenal in 1946.  It has a round, low wall receiver.  The bore is bright, rifling is strong, and the muzzle has not been counterbored.  Numbers match on the barrel, bolt (electro-pencil), magazine floorplate, and buttplate.  It was imported to the US by CAI and has a discreet import mark on the left side of the receiver just above the wood.  I purchased it on February 14, 2002 from AIM, still completely wrapped with waxed paper and string from the arsenal, opened only where the import marks had been applied.  After debating about leaving it wrapped, I unwrapped it, cleaned it, and shot 20 rounds through it before thoroughly cleaning and lubricating it again.  It hasn't been shot since, and for the last 10 years it has been a safe queen.  The stock still shows light marks where the string held the waxed paper against the shellac.  The bearing surface which supports the bayonet locking device when the bayonet is swung forward has almost no marks.  The pictures tell the story of the condition.  Note the shellac from the arsenal still present on the sling escutcheons, the nearly unmarked bayonet lock bearing surface, and the light string/waxed paper marks on top of the stock about 1" apart.  High resolution pictures are available on request.

FTF transaction only.  Must present government picture ID showing you are a resident of Ohio of legal age to purchase this firearm.

(If you are confused about all the $90 Mosin-Nagants flooding the market these days, those are M91/30 models with detachable bayonets. That's a good deal on those older, longer rifles. You should get one of those too before the supply dries up, like it has on the M44 model I am selling.)
